<TITLE> Indices on bourses see sharp increase </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 7 (bdnews24.com)Indices on the country's bourses witnessed a sharp increase Thursday led by bank, mutual fund and power and insurance issues. The general index touched the 3000 mark again in two days due to investors' buying spree anticipating inflow of huge funds as merchant banks will be allowed to offer loans to their clients at 1:1 ratio next week, according to market observers. "As the regulators decided to lift the restriction on margin loans effective from next week investors are now on buying securities hoping that funds would be injected in the market," said a top official of a brokerage house, preferring anonymity. He also said institutional buyers were active to garner benefits of the recent stock price fall. Turnover on the bourses also witnessed a sharp increase. Dhaka Stock Exchange (DSE) turnover surged to Tk 2.71 billion from Wednesday's Tk 1.95 billion, while that on the Chittagong Stock Exchange (CSE) increased to Tk 536.73 million from Tk 404.58 million DSE general index maintained an upward trend throughout the day with some slight declines and loss recovering to finish upbeat. The benchmark DGEN or general index closed 55.50 points or1.88 percent up at 3000.16. The DSI or all share price index ended on 2523.08, up 43.07 points or 1.73 percent. The bourse's blue chip DSE-20 also advanced 32.69 points, or 1.39 percent, to end at 2381.07. Gainers outnumbered losers 176 to 49 with some seven scrips holding steady. AB Bank topped the turnover board, ending 9.15 percent up at Tk 2889.50. Jamuna Oil second in line with AB Bank fell 1.14 percent to Tk 363.90. Meghna Petroleum also slumped 1.30 percent to finish at Tk 364.40. Grameen Mutual Fund One continued to gain from Wednesday to close at Tk 125, up 1.37 percent. IFIC Bank advanced 3.81 percent to Tk 2842.50. Among the other scrips on the turnover board, AIMS 1st Mutual Fund, AB Bank, Power Grid Company of Bangladesh and Far East Life Insurance also gained. Summit Power and BRAC Bank, however, declined. Karnaphuli Insurance, BDCOM Online, Pragati Insurance, Perfume Chemicals and Purabi General Insurance topped the gainers. The day's major losers were M Hossain Garments, Rose Heaven Ball, Samata Leather, Eastern Insurance and BGIC. All the CSE indices ended upbeat on Thursday. The CSCX or selective categories index rose 89.30 points, or 1.85 percent, to end on 4911.89. The CASPI or all share price index ended at 7634.08, up 130.35 points or 1.73 percent. The blue-chip CSE-30 index gained 145.61 points, or 2.17 percent, to end on 6826.09. Of the traded issues, 106 advanced, 33 declined and six remained unchanged. bdn
